[[File:Murayama-jinja (Shikokuchuo), torii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Torii}}]]
'''Murayama Shrine''' (むらやまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Doi-chō Tsune, {{ill|lt=Shikokuchūō|Q838666|qid=Q838666|1=Shikokuchūō}}, {{ill|lt=Ehime Prefecture|Q123376|qid=Q123376|1=Ehime Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=myōjin taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and its former rank in the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The main deity is {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|qid=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu-kōdaijin|1=Amaterasu}}. {{ill|lt=Empress Saimei|Q235296|qid=Q235296|1=Empress Kōgyoku}}, {{ill|lt=Emperor Tenji|Q314802|qid=Q314802|1=Emperor Tenji}}, and {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane|Q2564508|qid=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|1=Ame-no-Koyane}} are additionally enshrined.

=== Overview ===
Since shrine buildings and old records were burned in war fire in {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 13 ({{ill|lt=1585|Q6736|qid=Q6736|1=1585}}), the founding period is unknown. According to shrine tradition, Empress Saimei and Emperor Tenji were merged here in September of {{ill|lt=Hakuhō|Q11580612|qid=Q11580612|1=Hakuhō}} 3 ({{ill|lt=674|Q30302|qid=Q30302|1=674}}).

The shrine precinct is said to be the site of Iwase no Angū in Na-ōtsu, where Empress Saimei stayed while heading to Tsukushi to aid Baekje. There are also over 70 wooden statues, said to be attendants of Empress Saimei. A tradition also treats the "Otakarazuka" mound before the shrine as a mausoleum of a noble person.

Generally, Na-ōtsu is identified with Hakata Bay and Iwase no Angū with Miyake in Minami-ku, Fukuoka City. However, this shrine's origin account cites a passage in the '{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|qid=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}' saying "the imperial ship '''returned to''' Na-ōtsu and stayed at Iwase Angū," arguing that Empress Saimei returned by ship eastward from Iyu no Yukata ({{ill|lt=Dōgo Onsen|Q1037748|qid=Q1037748|1=Dōgo Onsen}}) in Iyo and stayed at this site.

In {{ill|lt=Ninju|Q1373077|qid=Q1373077|1=Ninju}} 3 {{ill|lt=853|Q30367|qid=Q30367|1=853}}, it was included in the myōjin festival. In {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 9 ({{ill|lt=867|Q30347|qid=Q30347|1=867}}) it rose to Junior Fifth Rank Lower, and in Jōgan 12 ({{ill|lt=870|Q23629|qid=Q23629|1=870}}) to Junior Fifth Rank Upper. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} it is listed as {{ill|lt=myōjin taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}.

It is said that in former times pilgrimage to {{ill|lt=Ise Jingū|Q687168|qid=Q687168|1=Ise Grand Shrine}} was called upper pilgrimage and worship at Murayama Shrine lower pilgrimage, and people from the thirty-three provinces of western Japan substituted worship at Murayama Shrine for pilgrimage to Ise.

It was revered by the {{ill|lt=Kōno clan|Q11554232|qid=Q11554232|1=Kōno clan}} and the Matsudaira lords of {{ill|lt=Saijō Domain|Q2212226|qid=Q2212226|1=Saijō Domain}}, and in the Edo period was one of six prayer shrines of Saijō Domain together with {{ill|lt=Isono Shrine|Q11379396|qid=Q11379396|1=Isono Shrine}} and others.

